To mock a function inside a function using Google Test (GTest), you can use the GMock framework provided by Google Test. GMock allows you to create mock objects for functions and classes, which can be used to mock the behavior of the function during testing.

Here is an example of how to mock a function inside a function using GMock:

Suppose you have the following function `foo` that calls another function `bar`:

```cpp
// Your header file
class MyClass {
public:
    virtual int bar() { return 10; }
    int foo() {
        return bar();
    }
};
```

To mock the `bar` function inside the `foo` function for testing, you can create a mock class using GMock:

```cpp
#include <gmock/gmock.h>

class MockClass : public MyClass {
public:
    MOCK_METHOD(int, bar, (), (override));
};
```

Then, in your test case, you can create an instance of the `MockClass` and specify the behavior of the `bar` function using GMock expectations:

```cpp
#include <gtest/gtest.h>
#include <gmock/gmock.h>

TEST(MyClassTest, FooTest) {
    MockClass mockObj;

    // Specify the behavior of the bar function
    EXPECT_CALL(mockObj, bar()).WillOnce(::testing::Return(5));

    // Create an instance of MyClass and call the foo function
    MyClass obj;
    int result = obj.foo();

    // Verify the result
    ASSERT_EQ(result, 5);
}
```

In this test case, we are mocking the `bar` function inside the `foo` function by creating a mock object `mockObj` of the `MockClass` and using GMock expectations to specify the behavior of the `bar` function. This allows us to test the `foo` function independently of the `bar` function.

